Title: Research 2 Locking procs
Description:
information.

Hi Everyone,

;

5 incidents of long process blocking occurred on ELKPRDSQLCLUS1 between 9 PM CST yesterday and 5 AM CST today. The chart below shows culprit processes (responsible for blocking) as thick bars and victim processes (which were blocked by culprits) as thin bars. There were 5 culprits.

All of these processes (culprits and victims) came from Microsoft Dynamics AX running on host servers ELKPRDAX1, ELKPRDAX2, and ELKPRDAX3.

In every incident, the problem was on the application side: the culprit process went idle without committing the last transaction, which resulted in the culprit holding locks on tables it had changed earlier, even through it wasn’t running any queries. This happens when the application executes BEGIN TRANSACTION, then changes data in tables through INSER/UPDATE/DELETE queries, and never executes COMMIT TRANSACTION or ROLLBACK TRANSACTION. This is a bug in the application that it allows such scenario and doesn’t have any safety process to check for such abandoned processes and terminate them (which causes a rollback and releases locks).

;

In incidents 1, 4, and 5, blocking occurred on the table [AX2009_SPARTON_PRD].[dbo].[REQPLAN] (i.e. the culprit process was holding an exclusive lock on that table while sitting idle, while victim processes were trying to access the table and were blocked).

In incidents 2 and 3, blocking occurred on the table [AX2009_SPARTON_PRD].[dbo].[SMMTRANSLOG].

;

This is an application problem that can’t be fixed from the SQL Server side. If you like, I can implement auto-killing of blocker processes after they cause this problem for a certain number of minutes, which isn’t a cure for the root cause, but a pain-killer.

;

;

Thanks,

Andrew

708-609-8783

;

Title: Fix ShopFloor Header
Description:
I’ve got a growing chorus of complaints that RoHS no longer appears in the banner (header) of routers for lead-free builds. Right or wrong, this has apparently been the only cue production has used from the beginning of time to determine what is and what is not to be built using lead free vs. lead bearing solder. Not one person I’ve talked to on the floor knows what the P&IC code is or how to interpret it. This is causing situations in which the operators have no idea whether or not an assembly should be produced using lead-free or leaded process and could easily result in a RoHS violation if not addressed immediately.

;

Please advise, was this RoHS info. Removed from the router header on purpose? And despite intent, what resources does the floor have to prompt them to use P&IC code and subsequently interpret it?

;

Prior lead free cues:

;


Current router header, note missing P&IC breakout and lack of ROHS declaration banner:

Description:
Add "https://www.primus-tech.com/wp-content/uploads/Spartronics-Terms-Conditions-Supplement-Rev-July-25-2017-Copy-Copy-Copy.pdf"

To POs




Hi Mike,

The AS9100D audit went fairly well – we only received 3 NCs rather than the 8 we had last year.; I need your help on the NC#3

AS9100D NC#3; Minor

Purchasing - Purchasing

AS9100D:8.4.3 Information for External Providers - The process for providing information to external providers in the form of adequate communications of requirements is not effective in all cases.

Objective Evidence:; Spartronics Supplier Flow-downs contained in Spartronics; T’s & C’s do not refer to or contain all the required AS 9100 requirements stated in Primus Technologies ( now Spartronics Williamsport Inc.) PO; Terms and Conditions; Supplemental; Rev. 7/2017

No Containment Required

When Al did the Audit in purchasing, he asked: how do the suppliers get the T&C’s?; They told hm there is a hot link on the PO that brings them to the Spartronics T&Cs. He had them print it out, paused a moment and said ‘This will not do .. where are all the AS9100 requirements?’ He also remarked that he believed we had it covered in the past.; I remembered that we had the supplemental T&Cs in our ‘important papers’ on our web site.; We printed that out and he said ‘YES’, I knew it existed! but how do I get to it from the Spartronics website?; We found that in the Spartronics T&Cs on page 6 section 28 it mentioned ‘PE-5590’.; Randy found it through a google search – it was from SPARTON.; Al compared the two and said only the old Primus supplemental sufficiently covered the AS9100D requirements, so he wrote it up

What we would like your help in is:

For our Remedial NC Action/s I was instructed to

  1. downloaded the old Primus supplemental - done
  2. changed the Primus to Spartronics - done
  3. put it on our old website - done
  4. Have Mike add another hotspot
    (temporary) to the POs that links to the modified supplemental via our old Website: https://www.primus-tech.com/wp-content/uploads/Spartronics-Terms-Conditions-Supplement-Rev-July-25-2017-Copy-Copy-Copy.pdf

For our final correction – we have SPARTRONICS CEO, Annette Cusworth, looking over the Sparton & the Primus supplements and will decide on aa final copy for Spartronics.; Then the temporary link can disappear.

Al seemed happy with that resolution.; The mission now is catching from this point further, all of the new Pos generated for vendors, so we can insure they are getting the proper supplemental that meets all of the AS9100D requirements.

Title: Defect Collection Upgrade
Description:
Gentlemen,

I had an idea I brought up in our defect meeting regarding the ability to allocate a single defect to multiple employees. I ran it by the group to hear their thoughts and there were no objections; nothing but positive feedback. ;
The idea is to be able to enter multiple employees for the same defect. This doesnt mean its required, only that you have an option to do so.
For example, many times an operator is getting hit for missing a defect during inspection and the person whos actually responsible for the defect or for not checking their own work is not, and vice versa.
It eliminates picking and choosing and the operators do not feel they are being singled out, when clearly both are responsible. It promotes equal accountability and fairness across the board.
Other benefits include, greater awareness and visibility … operators may not even be aware of a defect they had a "hand" in because it is allocated to someone else.
It promotes the importance of checking ones work, which will help to achieve our goal of eliminating all defects, without having to inflate our numbers and adding additional defects into the system.
Theres more but thats the basic premise.
Is this something that can be done or we can do? Do you see any concerns or issues from a technical standpoint?
Oh … I also spoke with Margie as well, because any changes will be across the board in both buildings. She loved it and gave the go ahead to see if we cant get this done. .

Please let me know your thoughts,
Lenny ;

Title: PO Spend
Description:
Hi Mike,

Nice meeting you (through email for now). As Paul mentioned, we are working on the supply chain organization assessment and spend analysis. We need your help to get the data requirements below asap to get started, so please let me know if you have any questions on these.

Also we would like to set up time with you, as well as any other key members of your supply chain organization (for early next week). These could be some of your key buyers, admin, as well as any others that could help us understand the current organization, structure, supply chain processes (i.e., sourcing, quoting, purchasing, planning, inventory and supplier management), systems and tools.

So please let us know the names, titles, and emails of the folks you’d recommend we should meet with so we can reach out to them.

Primus Data Request:

Please provide the following prioritized data (spend and revenue data should be for the date period of 07/01/19 to 06/30/20) by NLT next Tuesday 1/12:

  1. Purchase data (please see the attachment for the template which includes the fields required, and some examples for reference)
  2. Indirect spend – freight, packaging, etc.
  3. Sales data – per customer and business segment
  4. Supply chain (SC) org charts and employee file (list of names, titles, contact info, etc.)
  5. SC contracts and agreements
  6. Supplier scorecards and internal dashboards (e.g., MBRs, QBRs, etc.)
  7. SC processes, policies and procedures

Title: On Order Excess Safety Stock
Description:
We need to align the On Order Excess with the Derived purchasing schedule in MRP. This will probably need changed in Purchasing Dashboard and Company Report Card
Example part:;A34015;

The derived purchasing schedule is adding 330 to demand and coming up with -8:

On order 992 + Inventory 1914 ;= 2906

Demand 2584 + Safety stock 330 = 2914

Net excess -8

The base MRP is netting out to 322 excess because you have 1914 on hand well over the required 330.

On order 992 + Inventory 1914 ;= 2906

Demand 2584

Net excess = 322


Apparently Per Raytheon Project X this is how this is sapposed to be drivin and the Derived Purchasing Schedule "middle of the req in MRP reports" does this.


Mike

Title: KIT OTD Should Start Date vs Start Date
Description:
We need a way to over ride the system without changing planning lead time or due date.
We also need a way to feed the floor based on capacity but not penalize purchasing/marketing on the KIT OTD.
We also need a way to move the Due Date sometimes to re-prioritize the floor but not effect the date the kit should start.
For KIT OTD calculations instead of using Due Date - Planning lead time, use Start Date.
This is also simpler and more stock Macola.
Leave ShouldStartDate on all report so this can still be monitored.
Most times ShouldStartDate and Start Date are the same, but we have instances where it is off an noone can see it.
Mike

Title: Box builder viper
Description:
The goal: automate the PCM assignment of MAC addresses and serials for IR PCM and remove any chance of misallocation.

The process: user enters Anumber, Shoporder, serial of board, and qty into new IR PCM Box Builder form.
Form generates QTY serials, 2*QTY MAC addresses (one from Viper block and one from PCM block), updates the two blocks to show the new usage, QTY labels, and QTY 3 sheet customer packets.

PCM and Viper have to be kept up to date with the Box Builder functions to avoid causing issues for other products. Data from Box Builder needs pushed into those databases.

Viper and PCM also need to have the following: admin consoles for Phil and Craig to update the blocks themselves, a lockout system to prevent race conditions between serial and MAC assignments from Box Builder, a progress bar (possibly replicated in Box Builder) to show how many MACs are left in each block.

Its important to also note that the creation of the Box Builder record first needs to make sure enough MACs can be assigned for the QTY and reject it if it cant.

The Box Builder records needs a TestChecklist and Inspection Sheet.

Mike,

To help streamline First Articles, I will need the following from IT.

;

-A program to supply accountability for all non SMT parts used on every assembly similar to SMT Reels.

;

First Articles can be broken down into the following:

Pre-start/ First process inspection – Approximately 50% of the time required to complete First Article

In-process inspections – Approximately 20% of the time required to complete First Article

Final First Article Inspection –Approximately 30% of the time required to complete First Article

;

The above programming would cut the time down for Pre-start/ First Process Inspection by approximately 20% and Final First Article Inspection by approximately 5%.

;

The time required to complete First Articles could be steam lined further by purchase of a AS91002 First Article Program.

“Visual FAIR® removes the administrative burden for your quality professionals. Visual FAIR® improves quality, eliminates waste, reduces lead time and cuts down the total cost of managing and producing FAIs.” (IPI Visual Fairs)

Tammy Marino

Title: New Program for ASM Fix
Description:
I would like to have an ASM OIB software program that clears a feeders status if it has a reel attached to it or not. Title: 2 test paths vsts-236
Description:
The Mac Address will not change between the A# and the R#. So if we issued a MAC as an A#, we can pull that and use the same one.

The scope of what is required has changed.

For an RMA, a unit could take one of 2 test paths. If it is a hardware failure (non-electrical), No High-Pot or ESS testing would be required- functional, power consumption, appearance, and weight only. So this would be an abbreviated PIR with validation. If it is an electrical failure, it would be a full PIR including all tests and all validations normally performed with a production unit along with validations.

We envision a check box to select which test path the unit will be validated against (Hardware / Electrical).

How long would it take to develop, test, and release this package.

Phil

Title: Cal database, redundant calibrations in History vsts-579
Description:
Our practice of abeyance works like this: Calibration is registered, then status is changed to STORED. When Equipment is placed into service, status is changed back to OK and cycle is adjusted to make proper due date of 1 cal cycle after date placed into service. We do not touch the calendar so the actual cal date is unchanged. Unfortunately a nuisnace redundant calibration is being generated in History. The rule for a calibration is: Status must contain OK AND a date must be selected on the calendar! If we dont touch the calendar, there should be no new calibration!!

;

;

Mike,

I couldn’t find the ticket, but I remember that the issue was the History table was showing redundant calibrations of the same date and this was the result of changing status, probably of calibrated equipment that was stored in abeyance and later placed into service. Our practice is to change the status from OK to STORED when the equipment is placed into abeyance. Then when ready to use the equipment, we change status back to OK and change the cycle days to make a due date equal to one calibration cycle after placed into service. This resulted in the unwanted redundant calibration date in History.

An example is below. It is not annoying enough for me to hunt these all down. I think I told Derek that if we don’t click on the calendar, there should be no calibration date added, and we don’t click on the calendar when we bring something out of abeyance.

We are not in any trouble over this, but it would be nice to have it fixed.

Thanks

from setup in CSetup

select new

;;; SetupName = alias.ObjectName,

;

Description:
Mike,

To help streamline First Articles, I will need the following from IT.

;

-A program to supply accountability for all non SMT parts used on every assembly similar to SMT Reels.

First Articles can be broken down into the following:

Pre-start/ First process inspection – Approximately 50% of the time required to complete First Article

In-process inspections – Approximately 20% of the time required to complete First Article

Final First Article Inspection –Approximately 30% of the time required to complete First Article

;

The above programming would cut the time down for Pre-start/ First Process Inspection by approximately 20% and Final First Article Inspection by approximately 5%.

;

The time required to complete First Articles could be steam lined further by purchase of a AS91002 First Article Program.

“Visual FAIR® removes the administrative burden for your quality professionals. Visual FAIR® improves quality, eliminates waste, reduces lead time and cuts down the total cost of managing and producing FAIs.” (IPI Visual Fairs)

The implementation of these programs will help to provide on time completion of First Articles.;


Tammy Marino

Title: Cal database, redundant calibrations in History vsts-579
Description:
Our practice of abeyance works like this: Calibration is registered, then status is changed to STORED. When Equipment is placed into service, status is changed back to OK and cycle is adjusted to make proper due date of 1 cal cycle after date placed into service. We do not touch the calendar so the actual cal date is unchanged. Unfortunately a nuisnace redundant calibration is being generated in History. The rule for a calibration is: Status must contain OK AND a date must be selected on the calendar! If we dont touch the calendar, there should be no new calibration!!

;

;

Mike,

I couldn’t find the ticket, but I remember that the issue was the History table was showing redundant calibrations of the same date and this was the result of changing status, probably of calibrated equipment that was stored in abeyance and later placed into service. Our practice is to change the status from OK to STORED when the equipment is placed into abeyance. Then when ready to use the equipment, we change status back to OK and change the cycle days to make a due date equal to one calibration cycle after placed into service. This resulted in the unwanted redundant calibration date in History.

An example is below. It is not annoying enough for me to hunt these all down. I think I told Derek that if we don’t click on the calendar, there should be no calibration date added, and we don’t click on the calendar when we bring something out of abeyance.

We are not in any trouble over this, but it would be nice to have it fixed.

Thanks

Picklist siplace update vsts-1248
Description:
Objective is to include searching the comments of a setup to find the setups related to a particular SMT Reels kit

Eric asked me to send you where the comments for setups are.

They are found in the [Root].[UserText]

;

Here is the linq that worked for me.

from setup in CSetup

join alias in AliasName on setup.OID equals alias.PID

join root in Root on setup.OID equals root.OID

where root.UserText.Length > 0

select new

{

;;; SetupName = alias.ObjectName,

;;; Comment = root.UserText,

}

;

Hope this helps.
